{"ts":1779525230657,"jobId":"f7fd6a53-c747-4e1b-9fed-f32f2d956850","action":"finished","status":"ok","summary":"I can see your Ubiquiti Travel Router availability monitoring system is running but encountering API rate limit issues. Let me provide a comprehensive analysis and practical solutions.\n\n## Current System Status\n\n**Cron Job Health:**\n- ✅ **Enabled**: Yes (Job ID: `f7fd6a53-c747-4e1b-9fed-f32f2d956850`)\n- ✅ **Schedule**: Every 30 minutes (`*/30 * * * *`)\n- ⚠️ **Last Run**: Failed with API rate limit error (06:30 UTC)\n- ✅ **Previous Run**: Successful (06:00 UTC)\n- ⏰ **Next Run**: Scheduled for 07:00 UTC\n\n**Product Status:**\n- ❌ **Availability**: SOLD OUT (confirmed by state file)\n- 📅 **Last Check**: 2026-05-23T06:06:37Z (about 2.5 hours ago)\n- 📊 **Consistency**: Product has remained sold out through 633+ checks\n\n## Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe cron job is using an LLM (`agentTurn`) to execute simple shell commands. This is inefficient because:\n1. **Each run consumes ~40-50K LLM tokens** - unnecessary overhead\n2. **`deepseek-3.2` has rate limits** - hitting API limits\n3. **Simple task, complex solution** - web scraping doesn't need LLM intelligence\n\n## The Better Solution Already Exists\n\nYou have a perfectly working shell script (`utr-availability-monitor.sh`) that does exactly what you need without LLM overhead. I tested it and it works correctly.\n\n## What You Can Do\n\nSince I can't modify cron jobs due to restrictions, here are your options:\n\n### Option 1: Set Up a System Cron Job (Recommended)\n\nAdd this to your system's crontab:\n\n```bash\n# Edit your crontab\ncrontab -e\n\n# Add this line (runs every 30 minutes)\n*/30 * * * * cd /home/node/.openclaw/workspace && TELEGRAM_TOKEN=\"YOUR_TOKEN_HERE\" ./utr-availability-monitor.sh >> /home/node/.openclaw/workspace/utr-monitor.log 2>&1\n```\n\n### Option 2: Create a Simple Daemon Script\n\nCreate a script that runs in a loop:\n\n```bash\n#!/bin/bash\n# /home/node/.openclaw/workspace/